.TH "TD\-RANGE" "1" "2026" "TARDIS Manual"
.SH NAME
td\-range \- expand a date expression into a start/end range
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]td range\f[R] \f[I]EXPRESSION\f[R] [\f[I]OPTIONS\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]td range\f[R] interprets a date expression as a time period and
expands it into a start and end datetime.
The output contains two lines: the start datetime followed by the end
datetime, separated by the delimiter (newline by default).
.PP
\f[B]Granularity expansion:\f[R] the range end is determined by the
smallest unspecified time unit.
For example:
.IP \[bu] 2
\[lq]this week\[rq] expands to Monday 00:00 through Sunday 23:59:59.
.IP \[bu] 2
\[lq]today\[rq] expands to 00:00:00 through 23:59:59 of the current day.
.IP \[bu] 2
\[lq]this month\[rq] expands to the first day through the last day of
the month.
.IP \[bu] 2
\[lq]tomorrow at 3pm\[rq] expands from 15:00:00 through 15:59:59 (hour
granularity, since minutes and seconds were unspecified).
.PP
When the same expression is used with the default \f[B]td\f[R] command
(without the \f[B]range\f[R] subcommand), only the start\-of\-period
instant is returned.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\-\-format\f[R] \f[I]FMT\f[R]
Output format for both start and end (strftime pattern or preset name).
See \f[B]docs/FORMAT\-SPECIFIERS.md\f[R] for the full reference.
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R], \f[B]\-\-timezone\f[R] \f[I]TZ\f[R]
IANA/Olson timezone to apply (e.g.\ \[lq]UTC\[rq],
\[lq]America/Sao_Paulo\[rq]).
.TP
\f[B]\-\-now\f[R] \f[I]DATETIME\f[R]
Override the current time (RFC 3339).
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R], \f[B]\-\-delimiter\f[R] \f[I]DELIM\f[R]
Delimiter between start and end in plain\-text output.
Defaults to a newline character.
Common values: \[rq] / \[lq],\[rq] \[en] \[lq],\[rq],\[lq].
.TP
\f[B]\-j\f[R], \f[B]\-\-json\f[R]
Output as a JSON object with \f[I]start\f[R], \f[I]end\f[R], and
\f[I]delimiter\f[R] fields.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\-\-no\-newline\f[R]
Suppress the trailing newline.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R], \f[B]\-\-verbose\f[R]
Print verbose diagnostics to stderr.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Print help information.
.SH EXAMPLES
Expand \[lq]this week\[rq] to start/end:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]this week\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
Expand \[lq]this month\[rq] with a custom format:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]this month\[dq] \-f \[dq]%Y\-%m\-%d\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
Expand \[lq]today\[rq] to a full day range:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]today\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
Hour\-level granularity (tomorrow at 3pm):
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]tomorrow at 3pm\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
Custom delimiter:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]this week\[dq] \-d \[dq] / \[dq] \-f \[dq]%Y\-%m\-%d\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
JSON output:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]this month\[dq] \-\-json \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
.PP
With explicit format:
.IP
.EX
td range \[dq]this week\[dq] \-f \[dq]%d/%m/%Y %H:%M\[dq] \-\-now 2025\-06\-24T09:00:00Z \-t UTC
.EE
